1. Vector/Array

Arrays can store only data type.

[Including Code]

a = c(1,3,5,7,9)
b = c('Kim','Lee','Michael','Lee')

#Get the first element
a[1]
## [1] 1
a[2:5]
## [1] 3 5 7 9
length(a)
## [1] 5
sum(a)
## [1] 25
mean(a)
## [1] 5
a+1
## [1]  2  4  6  8 10
#Compare elements
a==3
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE
#Find the index
which(a==5)
## [1] 3
#Get the element with an index
a[which(a==5)]
## [1] 5
which(b=='Lee')
## [1] 2 4
#Count the matched
length(which(b=='Lee'))
## [1] 2

2. List

A list is an R structure that may contain objects of any other types, including other lists. List items need to be pointed by [[index]] (double square brackets) List can make tree-like data

[Including Code]

#List
L = list(ids=1:5, whos=c('Kim','Lee','Choi'))

names(L)
## [1] "ids"  "whos"
L[[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
L$ids
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
L$whos
## [1] "Kim"  "Lee"  "Choi"
L$whos[1]
## [1] "Kim"
L[[1]][5]
## [1] 5

3. DataFrame

A data frame is a table or a two-dimensional array-like structure in which each column contains values of one variable and each row contains one set of values from each column

5. Json

(Data Expression Sharing)

JSON: JavaScript Object Notation

JSON is a syntax for storing and exchanging data. JSON is text, written with javascript obect notation.

[Including Code]

item1 = list(name='Lee',age=35)
item2 = list(name='Kim',age=25)
item3 = list(name='Smith',age=40)

members = list(item1,item2,item3)

library(rjson)

toJSON(members)
## [1] "[{\"name\":\"Lee\",\"age\":35},{\"name\":\"Kim\",\"age\":25},{\"name\":\"Smith\",\"age\":40}]"
con = file('test.json')

writeLines(toJSON(members),con)

group = fromJSON(file='test.json')

all.equal(members,group)
## [1] TRUE

6. Function

One of the great strengths of R is the users ability to add functions. The structure of a function is given below.

myfunction <- function(arg1, arg2, ){

statements

return(object)

}

[Including Code]

myfunc = function(a,b) {return(a+b)}
myfunc(1,2)
## [1] 3
myfunc = function(a,b,c=100) {return(a+b+c)}
myfunc(1,2)
## [1] 103
myfunc(1,2,1000)
## [1] 1003
myfunc = function(a) {if(a==1) TRUE else FALSE}
myfunc
## function(a) {if(a==1) TRUE else FALSE}
myfunc(1)
## [1] TRUE
myfunc(2)
## [1] FALSE
b = c(1:5)
b
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
for(i in b) {print(myfunc(i))}
## [1] TRUE
## [1] FALSE
## [1] FALSE
## [1] FALSE
## [1] FALSE

7. Save

save: writes an external representation of R objects to the specified file.

  1. save.image(file=.Rdata), save.image() ==> save all
  2. save.image(variable, file=variable.Rdata) ==> save variable

8. Apply

returns a vector or array or list of values obtained by applying a function to margins of an array or matrix.

lapply returns a list of the same length as X, each element of which is the result of applying FUN to the corresponding element of X.

apply(X, MARGIN, FUN, )

MARGIN: 1-> Row way, 2-> Column way

[Including Code]

x = cbind(x1 = 3,x2 = c(4:1,2:5))
dimnames(x)[[1]] <- letters[1:8]

#radian value change
y = sin(x*pi/180)

plot(x,y,type='o',pch='+')

library(rgl)

plot3d(rnorm(100),rnorm(100),rnorm(100))
test_data = data.frame(x=rnorm(100),y=rnorm(100),z=rnorm(100))
plot3d(test_data)
head(test_data)
##            x          y          z
## 1 -0.4034828  1.2915066 -1.2693690
## 2 -2.2936411 -0.8660113  0.5598954
## 3 -0.2131388  0.3368339  0.3330266
## 4  0.1427311  0.1952335  1.0400611
## 5 -0.8902318  0.8748538 -0.4198883
## 6 -0.2211977 -0.2751247  2.2335713
plot3d(NULL,xlab='')
r=10
for (p in seq(0,180,10)) {
  q = seq(0,360,10)
  x = r *sin(p*pi/180)*cos(q*pi/180)
  y = r *sin(p*pi/180)*sin(q*pi/180)
  z = r *cos(p*pi/180)
  points3d(x,y,z)
  lines3d(x,y,z,col='red')
}

15. Clustering

[Including Code]

num_of_clusters=5
num_of_elements=200

x = sample(1:1000,num_of_elements,replace=F)
y = sample(1:1000,num_of_elements,replace=F)

t_data = data.frame(x=x,y=y)
head(t_data)
##     x   y
## 1 426 434
## 2 345 169
## 3  65 999
## 4 795 224
## 5 972 869
## 6 256 796
plot(x,y,cex=0.1)

res = kmeans(t_data,num_of_clusters)

for (i in 1:num_of_clusters) {
  for (j in which(res$cluster==i)) {
  lines(c(res$centers[i,1],t_data[j,1]),
       c(res$centers[i,2],t_data[j,2]),
       col=i+3)
}
  points(res$centers[i,1],t_data[i,2], col='red',cex=2)

  text(res$centers[i,1],t_data[i,2],labels=paste('center-',i),pos=3,cex=0.7)

}
